article.headline: 3s by Bibby, Miller help Sacramento pull away
article.linkText: Kings hand Hawks sixth straight loss
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Brad Miller had his third straight double-double and hit a big 3-pointer late to help the Sacramento Kings hold off the Atlanta Hawks 98-86 Friday night. Miller finished with 17 points and 12 rebounds and Peja Stojakovic scored 31 for the Kings, who have won six of seven games. Atlanta guard Jason Terry, coming off his first scoreless game in more than two years, had 25 but couldn't stop the Hawks from losing their sixth in a row. Shareef Abdur-Rahim added 21 points and 10 rebounds. The Hawks closed within 84-81 on a 3-pointer by Jacque Vaughn with 5:18 left, then had a chance to get closer after Mike Bibby missed a jumper. But Terry's wide-open shot from the baseline bounced off the rim, and Bibby later hit a 3 to boost the lead to six. After Stephen Jackson had a shot blocked, Miller made only his fifth 3-pointer of the season for a 90-81 lead, and the Hawks never recovered. Miller has scored at least 12 points in 10 of the past 11 games, teaming with Vlade Divac to give Sacramento a tough tandem in the paint. In his previous game, Miller had 21 points, 14 rebounds and nine assists in a victory over the New Orleans Hornets, narrowly missing the second triple-double of his career. The other one came earlier this season against the Orlando Magic. Stojakovic, as always, did most all of his scoring from outside, including a run of seven consecutive points late in the third quarter to give the Kings a 10-point lead. He hit a 3 and two other long jumpers, prompting one fan to yell ``Layup!'' each time he shot. Sacramento took an 80-69 lead on a 3-pointer by Bobby Jackson early in the fourth before the Hawks rallied to within three. Game notes
In the first half, Atlanta C Nazr Mohammed went down with an injury just as the Hawks had a turnover. Sacramento inbounded with Mohammed writhing on the court, but Dion Glover had a steal and quickly called timeout so Mohammed could be helped to the bench. ... Kings F Tony Massenburg got a technical early in the fourth quarter after he was called for an offensive foul. He threw an elbow at Abdur-Rahim's chin, then argued when the foul was called.
